<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-933-684  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 933 684.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Dec 4 1989 v6 n48 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FCC orders RBHCs to end strategic pricing. (Federal CommunicationsCommission, regional Bell holding companies)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taff, Anita.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) makes a major policyreversal preventing the regional Bell holding companies fromstrategically pricing special-access services.andP;  The FCC said thatmarket conditions no longer exist that necessitate specialpricing, and that the practice has resulted in inflatedprivate-line fees.andP;  In fact, the FCC has ordered several localcarriers to pay refunds of up to $75 million in overcharges.andP;  Thenew policy ends years of bitter feuding among the local carriers,FCC and users groups.andP;  In addition, the InternationalCommunications Assn says that the action will prevent the regionalBell companies from overcharging for special access in the future.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     United States. Federal Communications CommissionBell Regional Holding CompaniesTelecommunicationsPriceAccess RightsGovernment Regulation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>